I personally don't like null, either, since I see it as anti-pattern. Why I put null in this draft was I saw `return null` as well in the source code and would like to make it consistent in the project. And I thought null check is similar as isWFConfig() check.

Right, functional/streams would benefit a lot from Optional. Anyway, I would implement this in the way of using isWFConfig(). 

FYI, my opinion is we could use Optional in this way like this, which might look more intuitive to me than null/exception.
```java
  public static Optional<WorkflowConfig> parseWorkflowConfig(HelixProperty property) {
    Map<String, String> configs = property.getRecord().getSimpleFields();
    if (!configs.containsKey(WorkflowConfigProperty.Dag.name())) {
      return Optional.empty();
    }
    return Optional.of(Builder.fromMap(configs).setWorkflowId(property.getId()).build());
  }
